// Construct oto using...
oto = new OtoEntry();
// You can give all fields at once,
// where order is (fileName, alias, left, consonant, right, preUtterance, overlap).
// By the way, these name above are the property name to use when accessing fields
oto2 = new OtoEntry("a.wav", "a", 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 1);
// Or you can maully get/set them
oto.fileName = "b.wav";
oto.left = oto2.left;

// Also you can deep copy one from another
oto3 = new OtoEntry(oto2);

// Get and modify source oto data via data array:
data[0].alias = "TEST";
// You can add or delete items as you like
data.push(oto2);
data.splice(1, 2);
// And this array will be the result to save

// You can rename WAV file like this
WAVFileAPI.renameFile(data[0].fileName, "a.wav");
// These renaming will be performed only after you click "OK" and confirmed to do so

// You can get the length of a WAV file like this (in ms)
WAVFileAPI.getWAVLength("a.wav");

// WAVFileAPI will find these file under the same folder of the oto.ini you open, 
// and you can ask it to use your system encoding to represent Shift-JIS, 
// which is a common case for users with non-Japanese systems.

// And you can use console API to log what you need
console.log("Hey!")

